Namaste madam,


I will share a few freewheeling thoughts.

In the beginnin=
g, it is useful to have an intellectual understanding. Reading books and ta=
lking to people tells us what is permanent and what is not and how to think=
 and act.

But, just reading books and having an intellectual understanding=
 of liberation is not jnana yoga - it is merely an interest in it. To be a =
jnana yogi, one must imbibe that wisdom into one's actions, thoughts and ev=
en instincts, i.e. one must overcome attraction and aversion to things and =
develop equal vision. But, there are innate instincts from millions of live=
s that cannot be overcome just like that. It takes time and practice.

Now,=
 different circumstances may trigger our instincts differently. So one may =
avoid some circumstances and actions that trigger more troublesome instinct=
s and deal with less troublesome instincts first. One can first try to over=
comes the easier instincts.

In the beginning, one has theoretical knowledg=
e and intellectual clarity. Then one engages in daily practices that calm t=
he mind so that there is some chance of resisting instincts during moments =
of crisis and challenge that come later in the day. :-) Of course, this pra=
ctice may be meditation or homam or even reading a spiritual book or contem=
plation of one's motives!

As one practices, one is trying to put intellect=
ual understanding to use. Over time, one's conditioning is overcome and one=
's neural networks are re-programmed. One becomes wiser (i.e. theoretical u=
nderstanding is imbibed into thinking and instincts).


Then one may learn =
to resist circumstances and actions that one avoided dealing with before (b=
ecause they trigger instincts too difficult to resist).

Though one in purs=
uit of wisdom may avoid some actions, because they trigger irresistible ins=
tincts, a jnani after some stage does not run after or away from specific a=
ctions. He has no agendas or desires and deals with any circumstances that =
come one's way based on momentum from before and deals with them.

*       =
 *        *

As Vasishtha said, action and wisdom go hand in hand. Actions =
help you imbibe wisdom into your instincts. Wisdom enables better actions.
=

Upanishads give a nice analogy. One with only action and no knowledge is l=
ike a blind person running into a forest fire. One with only knowledge and =
no action, is like a legless person who helplessly looks at the forest fire=
 rushing at one. He knows it will kill him, but he can't do anything about =
it!

A bird cannot fly by flapping one wing. But, at the same time, there i=
s no formula for how to fly. A bird starts flapping both wings arbitrarily =
and yet does not fly. As it tries, oneday its neural networks are programme=
d to send the right signals to right nerves in the right order and it just =
flies!

Similarly, one cannot free oneself by just stressing knowledge (int=
ellectual understanding) or physical/mental action. One engages in both arb=
itrarily, without the right balance, one oneday one's instincts are correct=
ly programmed to allow a takeoff!

*        *        *

Meditating in front=
 of fire is powerful and transformational. Really, all you need is a bright=
 fire in which you imagine divinity. Some procedures and devised to give th=
at sense of sacredness and divinity, but all you really need is fire.

But,=
 if homam is not attractive to one, that is fine. One can just meditate. Or=
 just chant God's name. Or just read books. Or contemplate. But add some ne=
w practices that calm the mind, if you want to re-wire and re-program your =
brain. Brain is happy to persist with habits. Breaking old habits often req=
uires creating new habits (that are hopefully less problematic).

Spending =
a decent amount of time (e.g. half hour or one hour) is better than just 5 =
min, though something is better than nothing.

Best regards,

Narasimha
